    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-03-26T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-03-26T13:00:00-05:00" n="114"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d114">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72119So/5</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SWG1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sharp</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-03-26T19:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 26, 1918, 7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 9.32 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3453. Your 3352, March 22, 4 p.m. Upon communicating this morning to the Minister
                    for Foreign Affairs the statement of the attitude of our Government in regard to
                    unofficial international conferences, Mr. <persName corresp="#p_PS1"
                        >Pichon</persName> asked me to transmit to you his sincere thanks for such a
                    clear and able exposition of that attitude. He told me that it exactly comported
                    with the views upon the subject entertained by not only the British and French
                    Governments, but by the Italian as well. He was very complimentary in his
                    reference <pb facs="0267" n="175" xml:id="pg_175"/> to the manner in which these
                    principles were fully set forth, saying that they well typified those upon which
                    all democratic governments should be founded and administered.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWG1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sharp</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
